{"id":"0809.0553","submitter":"Morbidelli Alessandro","authors":"Harold F. Levison, Morbidelli Alessandro (OCA), David Vokrouhlicky,\n  William Bottke","title":"On a Scattered-Disk Origin for the 2003 El61 Collisional Family - an\n  Example of the Importance of Collisions on the Dynamics of Small Bodies","comments":"The Astronomical Journal (2008) in press","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/0004-6256/136/3/1079","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The recent discovery of the 2003EL61 collisional family in the Kuiper belt\n(Brown et al., 2007) is surprising because the formation of such a family is a\nhighly improbable event in today's belt. Assuming Brown et al.'s estimate of\nthe size of progenitors, we find that the probability that a Kuiper belt object\nwas involved in such a collision since primordial times is less than roughly\n0.001. In addition, it is not possible for the collision to have occurred in a\nmassive primordial Kuiper belt because the dynamical coherence of the family\nwould not have survived whatever event produced the currently observed orbital\nexcitation. Here we suggest that the family is the result of a collision\nbetween two scattered disk objects. We show that the probability that a\ncollision occurred between two such objects with sizes similar to those\nadvocated in Brown et al. (2007) and that the center of mass of the resulting\nfamily is on an orbit typical of the Kuiper belt can be as large as 47%. Given\nthe large uncertainties involved in this estimate, this result is consistent\nwith the existence of one such family. If true, this result has implications\nfar beyond the origin of a single collisional family, because it shows that\ncollisions played an important role in shaping the dynamical structure of the\nsmall body populations that we see today.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Sep 2008 06:45:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-13"}
